 HashMaps. Up till now we've built a map abstraction, we've looked at how iterators work, we've created a

00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:16.800
 linked list implementation of the hash abstraction, and now we're going to go and build a hash

00:00:16.800 --> 00:00:24.400
 version and a tree version of that same thing. If you recall some lectures ago I read a Robert Frost

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:30.560
 poem, you know, miles to go before I sleep. Well, that's where we're at now. We're coming to the end

00:00:30.560 --> 00:00:35.760
 of this miles to go, although as you'll see the end is really just the beginning of the next phase.

00:00:35.760 --> 00:00:43.440
 And with a little foreshadowing, if you have been with me for a very long time, all the way

00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:48.400
 since Python for Everybody, which for me was recorded a number of years ago already,

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:54.800
 this is the first complete piece of code that I showed you, and that was the code to count the

00:00:54.800 --> 00:01:01.360
 number of words in a file by splitting them, then creating a dictionary, and then counting them.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:07.760
 Now we're going to finish this lecture by implementing this in C, but I'm getting ahead

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:14.640
 of myself. So the idea here is we're exploring, you know, different key value implementation

00:01:14.640 --> 00:01:22.000
 alternatives. We built an unordered Java-based hash map, which is like a Python 2 dictionary.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:28.880
 If you recall, Python 2 had unordered hash maps, which meant you sort of ended up with your stuff

00:01:28.880 --> 00:01:33.120
 coming out in a random order. It was the same order, but every time you inserted something,

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:39.360
 the order might change. Now Python 3, they tend to, later versions of Python 3, they tend to be

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:47.520
 ordered, which are more like the list map that we did. We're going to have a map that is sorted,

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:56.720
 that's more like Java's tree map with an iterator, and it is sort of chapter 6.5 or section 6.5 of

00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:06.240
 the book, and it is a combination of a tree map and a linked list map, but Java doesn't have such

00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:10.400
 thing, which really kind of surprises me. They got a tree map and they got a hash map, but they don't

00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:19.200
 have a linked tree map or a linked map. So here we go. Now these, the two abstractions, I mean,

00:02:19.200 --> 00:02:24.640
 two implementations we're going to build, kind of, you see them in Python, you see them in C++,

00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:30.800
 and you pretty much see them in Java as well, but we're going to do our own thing.

00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:43.040
 So I would say to you when you're writing this code, I don't want you to think that when I wrote

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:48.400
 this code that I gave you as samples or when I wrote these slides, that it was easy for me.

00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:56.400
 The concept of trees and hashes are pretty straightforward, but then you got to solve

00:02:56.400 --> 00:03:02.080
 the little problems of how to take the previous and hook it to the current and hook the next to the

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:08.400
 current next to the next from the preview. And so you've got to draw pictures, and this is actual

00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:12.720
 picture that I drew. I really wrote all this code from scratch. I mean, I didn't come up with the

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:18.320
 idea of a tree from scratch, but I wrote this code from scratch. And you can see that the,

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:25.040
 like when I was building the tree map, my goal was to find the right place in the tree to insert

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:32.000
 the next item. And so you see I've got this 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13. So I kind of constructed this tree

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:37.040
 that was right, it was in order. And then I was trying to figure out where I might put 4 and where

00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:44.800
 I might put 8 and where I might put 14. And then I kind of had this notion when I was writing the

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:49.360
 picture that I, you'll see I had the words lowest, node, greater than, and then I cross them all out

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:53.760
 because that wasn't enough. And you'll see when we get there that I have the lowest node greater

00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:57.920
 than and the greatest node less than. And I've got to get both of those things. And so as we

00:03:57.920 --> 00:04:03.040
 work our way down the tree, we've got to keep track of this. I'm getting way ahead of myself.

00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:12.560
 Like many data structure programming tasks, they, you can draw the picture and it makes a lot of

00:04:12.560 --> 00:04:16.480
 sense. You see the hash map, which is the first one we're going to do. That's really just nothing

